Here is an example of a simple script that denies access to a website or service:
```
<?php
  // Deny access to this script if the user is not authorized
  if (!isset($_COOKIE['authorized'])) {
    header('HTTP/1.1 401 Unauthorized');
    header('Content-Type: text/plain');
    echo 'Access denied. You are not authorized to access this service.';
    exit;
  }
?>
```
This script checks if a cookie named "authorized" is set and exists. If it's not set, it sends a 401 Unauthorized response header and displays a plain text message saying "Access denied. You are not authorized to access this service." and exits.

You can also add more complex logic to this script to check for additional conditions, such as IP address, user agent, or other authentication mechanisms.

For example, you can use an IP blocking list:
```
<?php
  // Deny access to this script if the user's IP is in the block list
  $block_list = array('192.168.1.1', '192.168.1.2');
  if (in_array(ip2long($_SERVER['REMOTE_ADDR']), $block_list)) {
    header('HTTP/1.1 403 Forbidden');
    header('Content-Type: text/plain');
    echo 'Access denied. Your IP is blocked.';
    exit;
  }
?>
```
Or you can use a CAPTCHA to challenge the user:
```
<?php
  // Display a CAPTCHA challenge if the user is not authorized
  if (!isset($_COOKIE['authorized'])) {
    header('HTTP/1.1 403 Forbidden');
    header('Content-Type: text/html');
    echo '<html><body><h1>Access denied. Please solve the CAPTCHA:</h1><img src="captcha.php">';
    echo '<form action="verify.php" method="post">';
    echo '<input type="text" name="captcha" />';
    echo '<input type="submit" value="Submit">';
    echo '</form></body></html>';
    exit;
  }
?>
```
Remember to replace the `captcha.php` and `verify.php` files with your own implementation of the CAPTCHA challenge and verification script.

You can also use other methods such as IP geolocation, user agent checking, or API keys to restrict access to your website or service.
